  m_QuestionText:
  - FontSize: 2
    Text: What is the difference between a shader and a material?
  m_QuestionImage: {fileID: 0}
  m_Skills: Skill-L2-Art.Shad-1
  m_ShuffleAnswers: 1
  m_Answers:
  - IsCorrect: 1
    Text: A shader is a script that runs as part of the rendering process, and a
      material is an asset that specifies properties to a shader.
  - IsCorrect: 0
    Text: A shader is used in physically-based rendering to create photorealistic
      effects, and a material is used to increase performance.
  - IsCorrect: 0
    Text: A shader affects how light appears on an object, and a material affects
      its color.
  - IsCorrect: 0
    Text: They are actually the same thing.
  m_FeedbackCorrect: Shaders and materials work together to define all the characteristics
    of a mesh surface during the rendering process. A material is an asset that works
    with a shader to define how meshes will be rendered.
  m_FeedbackIncorrect: Shaders and materials work together to define all the characteristics
    of a mesh surface during the rendering process. A material is an asset that works
    with a shader to define how meshes will be rendered.
